  "prompt": "Does Java support Multiple Inheritance?",
  "response": "No, Java does **not** support multiple inheritance of classes.\n\nIn other words, a class in Java cannot directly inherit from more than one class.\n\n**Why not?**\n\nThe primary reason for this design choice is to avoid the \"Diamond Problem\" (also known as the Deadly Diamond of Death).\n\n**The Diamond Problem:**\n\nImagine a scenario where you have four classes:\n\n*   `A`: A base class.\n*   `B`: A class that inherits from `A`.\n*   `C`: A class that also inherits from `A`.\n*   `D`: A class that attempts to inherit from both `B` and `C`.\n\n```\n     A\n    / \\\n   B   C\n   \\ /\n    D\n```\n\nIf both `B` and `C` override a method defined in `A`, and `D` calls that method, which version of the method should `D` execute?  Should it be `B`'s version or `C`'s version?  This ambiguity is the Diamond Problem.  Different languages resolve this in different ways, often with complex rules.  Java designers chose to avoid this complexity altogether.\n\n**Alternatives to Multiple Inheritance in Java:**\n\nInstead of multiple inheritance of classes, Java provides alternative mechanisms to achieve similar functionality:\n\n1.  **Interfaces:**  A class can implement multiple interfaces.  Interfaces define a contract (a set of methods) that a class must implement.  Interfaces do not provide implementation (prior to Java 8).  This avoids the Diamond Problem because there's no method implementation coming from the inherited structures.\n\n    ```java\n    interface Interface1 {\n        void method1();\n    }\n\n    interface Interface2 {\n        void method2();\n    }\n\n    class MyClass implements Interface1, Interface2 {\n        @Override\n        public void method1() {\n            // Implementation of method1\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public void method2() {\n            // Implementation of method2\n        }\n    }\n    ```\n\n2.  **Composition:**  Instead of inheriting from multiple classes, a class can contain instances of other classes (composition).  This allows you to reuse functionality from those classes without the complexities of multiple inheritance.\n\n    ```java\n    class ClassA {\n        public void methodA() {\n            System.out.println(\"Method A from ClassA\");\n        }\n    }\n\n    class ClassB {\n        public void methodB() {\n            System.out.println(\"Method B from ClassB\");\n        }\n    }\n\n    class MyClass {\n        private ClassA classA = new ClassA();\n        private ClassB classB = new ClassB();\n\n        public void useMethodA() {\n            classA.methodA();\n        }\n\n        public void useMethodB() {\n            classB.methodB();\n        }\n    }\n    ```\n\n3.  **Default Methods in Interfaces (Java 8 and later):** Java 8 introduced default methods in interfaces.  These allow interfaces to provide a default implementation for a method.  While this seems like a step towards multiple inheritance, it's still constrained by the \"implements\" relationship. If a class implements multiple interfaces that provide conflicting default implementations, the class must override the method to resolve the conflict explicitly. This avoids the ambiguous nature of the diamond problem because the class is forced to decide.\n\n    ```java\n    interface MyInterface1 {\n        default void myMethod() {\n            System.out.println(\"Default implementation from MyInterface1\");\n        }\n    }\n\n    interface MyInterface2 {\n        default void myMethod() {\n            System.out.println(\"Default implementation from MyInterface2\");\n        }\n    }\n\n    class MyClass implements MyInterface1, MyInterface2 {\n        @Override\n        public void myMethod() {\n            // Must provide an implementation to resolve the conflict\n            System.out.println(\"Implementation in MyClass\");\n        }\n    }\n    ```\n\nIn summary, Java does not support multiple inheritance of classes to avoid the Diamond Problem.  Interfaces and composition are used as alternative mechanisms to achieve similar functionality while maintaining a cleaner and more predictable inheritance model.\n",
